What I say to my non-American friends
CAMBRIDGE – I often travel abroad, and my foreign friends always ask, with varying degrees of bewilderment: but what is going on in your country?
Here is what I tell them.
First, be careful not to make a mistake about the 2016 elections.
Unlike some comments, the American political system has not been swept by a wave of populism.
It is true that we have a long history of rebellion against the elites.
Donald Trump tapped into a tradition associated with leaders such as Andrew Jackson and William Jennings Bryan in the 19th century, and Huey Long and George Wallace in the 20th century.
Yet Trump came within nearly three million votes of winning the popular vote.
He won the elections by appealing to populist resentment in three states of the Rust Belt (Michigan, Pennsylvania, and Wisconsin), which had previously voted for the Democratic Party.
If hundreds of thousands of votes had been cast differently in these states, Trump would have lost the Electoral College and the presidency.
That said, Trump's victory raises the real issue of the rise in social and regional inequalities in the United States.
J.D. Vance's latest bestseller, Hillbilly Elegy, convincingly describes the significant difference between California and the Appalachians.
Research conducted by Princeton economists Anne Case and Angus Deaton shows that demographic trends among non-college-educated white individuals with low incomes are worse than those of African Americans, who historically occupied the bottom rung of inequality.
In 1999, mortality rates among White individuals who had not pursued higher education were around 30% lower than those of African Americans; in 2015, they were 30% higher.
In addition, employment in industry, which was once one of the main sources of high-paying jobs for white working-class people, has sharply declined over the last generation, to only 2% of the workforce.
These former Democratic voters were swayed by Trump's promises to make things happen and bring jobs back to the industry.
Paradoxically, Trump's efforts to repeal President Barack Obama's healthcare legislation may well make their lives even harder.
The second thing I tell my foreign friends is that one should not underestimate Trump's communication skills.
Many people are shocked by his rages on Twitter and by his scandalous contempt for facts.
But Trump is a veteran of reality television, where he learned that the key to success is monopolizing viewers' attention, and that the best way to do so is by making extreme statements, without worrying about the truth.
Twitter allows him to set his agenda and distract his critics.
What annoys commentators in the media and academic circles does not bother his supporters.
But as soon as he moves from his self-centered permanent campaign to attempts at governing, Twitter becomes a double-edged sword that deters some allies whom he desperately needs.
Thirdly, I tell my friends not to expect normal behavior.
Normally, a president who fails to win the popular vote moves toward the political center in order to attract more support.
That's what George W. Bush did successfully in 2001.
In contrast, Trump declares that he won the popular vote and by acting as if that were truly the case, he appeals to his base voters.
Although Trump made solid centrist appointments to the Department of Defense, State, and National Security, his choices for the Environmental Protection Agency and the Department of Health and Human Services are at the extreme right of the Republican Party.
His White House staff is divided between ideologues and pragmatists—and he intends to please both camps at once.
Fourthly, one must not underestimate American institutions.
Sometimes my friends talk as if the sky is falling on their heads and ask me if Trump is a narcissist as dangerous as Mussolini.
I told them not to panic.
The United States, despite their many problems, are not the Italy of 1922.
Our national political elites are often polarized; but the founders of America were just as polarized.
In the design of the United States Constitution, the founders' goal was not to ensure that the government would be harmonious, but to limit political power to a system of checks and balances that makes the exercise of these powers difficult.
A joke about this topic says that the founders created a political system such that it would be impossible for King George to rule over us — impossible for him or for anyone else.
Inefficiency was put at the service of freedom.
Trump's presidency is still in its early stages, and we cannot be certain what might happen after, say, a major terrorist attack.
So far, however, the courts, Congress, and the states have preserved this balance of power within the executive branch, as Madison wished.
And the permanent civil servants of the executive services still carry weight.
Finally, my friends are wondering what all this means for American foreign policy and for the liberal international order led by the United States since 1945.
Frankly, I don't know, but I'm less worried about China's rise than about Trump's.
Although American leaders, including Obama, have complained about free riders, the United States has long taken the lead in providing significant global public goods: security, a stable international reserve currency, relatively open markets, and the management of our planet's common resources.
Despite the problems of the international order under the direction of the United States, the world has prospered and poverty has been reduced under this order.
But no one can be certain that it will continue.
The United States will have to cooperate with China, Europe, Japan, and other countries to manage transnational issues.
During the 2016 campaign, Trump was the first candidate from a major party in 70 years to question the American alliance system.
Since taking office in January, statements by Trump and his members suggest he may continue.
The power to coerce and the power to persuade of the United States, after all, largely stem from the fact that the United States has 60 allies (while China only has a few).
But the stability of multilateral institutions, which help manage the global economy and the planet's common goods, is more uncertain.
Trump's Budget Director speaks of a budget of coercive power, with budget cuts made to the State Department and the United Nations system.
Other government members argue for replacing multilateral trade agreements with bilateral "fair and balanced" arrangements. Trump rejects Obama's efforts to address climate change.
I tell my friends that I would like to reassure them about these issues.
But I can't.
